=== 2.10 Sine and Cosine

Sine and cosine are periodic functions with period stem:[2\pi]:

stem:[\sin^2 x + \cos^2 x = 1] (Pythagorean identity)

stem:[\sin(x + y) = \sin x \cos y + \cos x \sin y]

In GPT, sinusoidal positional encoding (Chapter 5) uses sine and cosine at different frequencies to encode token position stem:[pos] and embedding dimension stem:[i]:

stem:[\text{PE}(pos, 2i) = \sin\!\left(\frac{pos}{10000^{2i/d}}\right)]

stem:[\text{PE}(pos, 2i+1) = \cos\!\left(\frac{pos}{10000^{2i/d}}\right)]

Because stem:[\sin] and stem:[\cos] are bounded in stem:[[-1, 1\]], they add a predictable, scale-limited signal to the embedding without dominating the learned content.

==== Scheme Implementation

[source,scheme]
----
(define (pe pos i d-model)
  (let ((freq (expt 10000.0 (/ (* 2.0 i) d-model))))
    (if (even? i)
        (sin (/ pos freq))
        (cos (/ pos freq)))))
----

==== Example

With stem:[d = 4] (four embedding dimensions), position stem:[pos = 0, 1, 2]:

[source,scheme]
----
(display (pe 0 0 4))   ; => sin(0) = 0.0
(display (pe 0 1 4))   ; => cos(0) = 1.0
(display (pe 1 0 4))   ; => sin(1/1) = ~0.841
(display (pe 1 1 4))   ; => cos(1/1) = ~0.540
----

Each position produces a unique pattern of sine/cosine values, allowing the model to distinguish tokens by position.
